e written word—in finance, as the fabric of many transactions and a means of capturing capital. Analysts and media figures understand financial talk as requiring a skill set distinct from conducting research or representing facts. Preda demonstrates that analysts and media professionals deploy expertise when they engage with audiences in ways that make it difficult to contest the claims conveyed in their talk.The Spectacle of Expertise is based on close observations of TV and radio studios in Hong Kong, a global financial center and a crucial gateway to China, including interviews with audience members and financial analysts who appear as regular guests. It offers new and global perspectives on the relationship between financial expertise and the media, the making of public-expert talk, and how expertise is used to legitimize financialization.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aFinance, Personal. 0aFinancial planners. 0aInvestment advisors. 0aMass media. 0aSocial media. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Media Studies.2bisacsh  aHong Kong.  aIrving Goffman.  aSociety for the Advancement of Socio-Economics.  aTV and radio.  abusiness.  aethnography.  afinancial expertise.  afinancial markets.  afinancial talk.  ainternational finance.  amarket interpretation.  amedia studies.  apublic-expert talk.  asocial media influence.  asociology of finance.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311074967040uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/pred2024640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231554572423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231554572/original  a978-3-11-074967-0  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL